    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I saw a note in the manual about how small things like insects or even ice buildup can cause that blockage. What exactly happens to the airspeed indicator if the pitot tube gets plugged up while the plane is in flight? Like, is it just totally dead, or does it give a wrong number?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the pitot tube gets plugged up while the plane is in flight, the airspeed indicator can behave in a few different ways, depending on the extent of the blockage and the design of the aircraft's instruments. In most cases, if the pitot tube is completely blocked, the airspeed indicator will likely show an erroneous reading, which could be either too high or too low, or it might even freeze up and stop working altogether.\n\nIn some aircraft, there are backup systems or alternate sources of airspeed data that can take over if the pitot tube fails. These systems may use static pressure measurements from other sources to provide a backup airspeed reading. However, if the pitot tube is completely blocked and there are no backup systems in place, the pilot may not have a reliable airspeed reading at all.\n\nIt's like trying to read a book with a torn page - you might be able to make out some of the words, but it's not going to be an accurate or complete picture. In the case of a blocked pitot tube, the pilot may not have a complete or accurate picture of the aircraft's airspeed, which could lead to dangerous situations. That's why it's so important to keep the pitot tube opening clear and free from",
      "source": "target",
